  <discussion>Atrichum angustatum is a small, dioicous species, easily distinguished by its narrow, channeled leaves with numerous, tall, wavy lamellae, and small, ± isodiametric, bulging-mammillose, papillose leaf cells.  A characteristic habitat for this species is mounds of subsoil thrown up by the roots of fallen trees.  All Atrichum species develop cuticular papillae to some degree, but in no case are they as evident as in this species.  Plants growing in more humid situations tend to be less strongly papillose.  The distinction between A. angustatum, with smooth cells, and A. xanthopelma and A. macmillanii, with papillose cells, is without merit.  The leaves of the type of  A. angustatum (from South Carolina) are strongly papillose.</discussion>
